
  <sn><md>### Properties of Colloids

Since `colloidal particles occur in a colloidal state`, soil colloids form a `dispersed phase`, dispersed in a **dispersion medium (soil solution)**.
Colloids exhibit distinct properties such as **adsorption, electronegative charge, Tyndall effect, Brownian movement, cataphoresis, electro-osmosis, coagulation**, and other related characteristics.

#### Summary of Key Colloidal Properties
+++ table
| **Property**               | **Description**                                              | **Key Concept**            |
| -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------- |
| **Adsorption**             | Large surface area allows colloids to `hold ions &amp; molecules`. | Surface activity           |
| **Electronegative Charge** | `Clay surfaces are negatively charged`, attracting cations.    | Ionic double layer         |
| **Tyndall Effect**         | `Visible scattering of light` through colloidal suspension.    | Light diffusion            |
| **Brownian Movement**      | `Random motion` due to particle repulsion.                     | Stability of colloid       |
| **Cataphoresis**           | `Movement of charged particles` in electric field.             | Determines particle charge |
| **Electro-osmosis**        | `Movement of liquid medium` under electric field.              | Charge effect on water     |
| **Coagulation / Dialysis** | Settling of colloids or `purification` by membrane.            | Stability &amp; separation     |
+++
